<body>
    <a href="../index.html" class="nav-back">← Home</a>

    <main class="page-main">
            <div class="page-content">
            <div class="warning-box">
                <strong>⚠️ Historical Document Notice</strong><br>
                This page contains historical documentation from the BOA/RCA/RP era. It is not the current authoritative specification of VCDesign. Please refer to the current Core specifications (core/core.yaml, core/policies.yaml, core/metrics.yaml) for authoritative guidance.
            </div>
            <p><em>This concept has been superseded by the Core + Policies + Metrics model. Refer to specs/core/ for current definitions.</em></p>
            <p><em>This document represents the conceptual lineage that led to the current model.</em></p>



<div class="auxiliary-container">

            <div class="intro">
                <p>This document serves as a guide for reading the VCDesign Narrative.<br>
                    It does not explain the philosophy,<br>
                    but is placed to visualize the "role position" where the reader already stands.</p>
                <p>This text gives no answers.<br>
                    Instead, it asks, "Where do you stand?"</p>
            </div>
            <p><em>This concept has been superseded by the Core + Policies + Metrics model. Refer to specs/core/ for current definitions.</em></p>
            <p><em>This document represents the conceptual lineage that led to the current model.</em></p>



            <h1>Why "Value Continuers" Become Necessary</h1>

            <h2>1. When a Traditional Restaurant Moves</h2>
            <p>Suppose a long-loved restaurant moves to another town.</p>
            <p>Is it the recipe that is inherited?<br>
                Is it the cooking procedure?<br>
                Is it the interior design?</p>
            <p>All are necessary, but serve alone, they are not enough.</p>
            <p>Gourmet customers immediately notice these discrepancies.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>The taste is the same, but something is different</li>
                <li>The atmosphere is reproduced, but it doesn't feel relaxing</li>
                <li>I don't feel like visiting as often as before</li>
            </ul>
            <p>It is exposed that value was not determined by the cuisine alone.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>2. The "Unexplainable Value" Gourmet Customers Feel</h2>
            <p>The value of that restaurant was:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>The relationship with the location</li>
                <li>The atmosphere inside the store</li>
                <li>The sense of distance with the staff</li>
                <li>The surrounding customer base</li>
                <li>The time spent in that place</li>
            </ul>
            <p>It was the "experience of eating at this restaurant" itself,<br>
                where such elements were woven together.</p>
            <p>And what is important is<br>
                the accumulation of judgments on <strong>why it was so</strong>.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Why was it this location?</li>
                <li>Why this price range?</li>
                <li>Why was this customer base accepted?</li>
            </ul>
            <p>These were correct judgments at a certain point in time.<br>
                I call this unit a "chapter".</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>3. During a Move, Judgments Float in the Air</h2>
            <p>When moving a store, many judgments float in the air.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Should this atmosphere be protected in the new town?</li>
                <li>Should the same sense of distance be maintained even if the customer base changes?</li>
                <li>If changing, how far is it okay to change?</li>
            </ul>
            <p>It cannot be decided now.<br>
                But it cannot be treated as if it didn't exist either.</p>
            <p>So people write on a whiteboard.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Judgment suspended</li>
                <li>Consultation required</li>
                <li>Must review later</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This is not an incomplete task.<br>
                It is <strong>a place to temporarily deposit judgments that could not be fully decided</strong>.</p>
            <p>In order to consult someone,<br>
                without forcing a conclusion,<br>
                but to not forget, it is placed where it can be seen.</p>
            <p>This whiteboard becomes a pool of judgments.<br>
                It is a place where judgments stay temporarily before a chapter begins.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>4. The Pool Must Be Retrieved</h2>
            <p>Judgments written on the whiteboard do not disappear naturally.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Decide someday</li>
                <li>Someone takes it on</li>
                <li>Pass it to the next chapter, or end it here</li>
            </ul>
            <p>If someone does not retrieve them,<br>
                the store cannot take the next step.</p>
            <p>If someone does not retrieve them,<br>
                the store cannot take the next step.</p>
            <p>It might not be the cook or the store manager.<br>
                But someone must:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Identify judgments that are not decided now</li>
                <li>Leave them in a form that won't be forgotten</li>
                <li>Retrieve them at the moment the chapter can begin</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This role must be undertaken.</p>
            <p>Gourmet customers do not verbalize it.<br>
                But they definitely sense it.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>This store continues with understanding</li>
                <li>Or is it just remaining by chance?</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The difference in value appears there.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>5. This Also Applies to Engineers</h2>
            <p>The story so far is about a restaurant.<br>
                But please try replacing it with your own work for a moment.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Are you only handing over deliverables?</li>
                <li>Are you leaving judgments on the whiteboard?</li>
                <li>Are you leaving it as "someone will think about it eventually"?</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Systems, products, and organizations are the same.<br>
                Value does not continue with implementation and optimization alone.</p>
            <p>Which judgments to inherit,<br>
                and which judgments to end.</p>
            <p>Depending on whether there is someone to take that on,<br>
                value quietly diverges.</p>
            <p>Am I now<br>
                placing which judgments in the pool?<br>
                And do I stand in a position to retrieve them?</p>

            <footer>
                © 2026 VCDesign
            </footer>
