<article>
            <h1>MANIFESTO</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">— Design Attitude of VCDesign —</p>

            <p>VCDesign is not a philosophy to optimize deliverables.</p>

            <p>It is a <strong>Design Attitude</strong><br>
                to prevent Judgment and Responsibility<br>
                from being severed by Time.</p>

            <p>To ensure the system continues to deliver value,<br>
                we adhere to the following five attitudes.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>1. Static Stability: Guarantee Current Judgment</h2>

            <p>We do not change the rules during execution.</p>

            <p>Judgment must be Closed<br>
                as either Affirmation, Negation, or Unknown.</p>

            <p>We guarantee the "Completion" of judgment<br>
                rather than the "Correctness" of the result.<br>
                We do not design judgments that cannot be closed.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>2. Dynamic Adaptability: Change for the Future</h2>

            <p>We do not define an eternal correct answer.</p>

            <p>To sustain value,<br>
                we observe environmental changes and rewrite rules.</p>

            <p>Changing not for optimization,<br>
                but for survival,<br>
                is a system obligation as a distinct judgment.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>3. Spatial Safety: Connect Safely with Others</h2>

            <p>We do not blur the Boundary of Responsibility.</p>

            <p>When chaining judgments,<br>
                we confirm that the counterpart is "Closed".</p>

            <p>We never connect<br>
                to entities where the locus of responsibility is unclear,<br>
                or where the boundary is undefined.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>4. Emergency Avoidance: Leave Danger Immediately</h2>

            <p>We do not tolerate the propagation of runaway processes.</p>

            <p>When the premise of connection collapses,<br>
                we immediately Reverse and withdraw without hesitation.</p>

            <p>We incorporate the courage to stop on the spot into the design<br>
                rather than allowing contamination to spread.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>5. Protocol of Demise: End Gracefully</h2>

            <p>We do not accept zombified processes.</p>

            <p>When value can no longer be maintained,<br>
                we acknowledge that the premise for continuing judgment is lost,<br>
                and gracefully abandon it.</p>

            <p>"Ending" is not a defeat.<br>
                It is a normal function for creating new value.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>About This Manifesto</h2>

            <p>This document is the <strong>Declaration of Design Attitude</strong> in VCDesign.</p>

            <p>Any design that does not agree with these five attitudes<br>
                shall not bear the name of VCDesign.</p>

            <hr>

            <h2>Positioning</h2>

            <ul>
                <li>Upper: VCDesign Constitution</li>
                <li>Prerequisite: PHILOSOPHY / Prelude</li>
                <li>This Document: Declaration of Design Attitude</li>
                <li>Lower: Narrative / Tools / Implementation</li>
            </ul>
        </article>

